image.altText: Michele Bullock fronting a Senate estimates hearing

items.synopsis: RBA governor Michele Bullock says while it is slowing, rental inflation is expected to hit 10 per cent per annum some time in the coming months. Follow the day's financial news on our live blog.

title.children: RBA's Bullock expects rental inflation to hit 10pc per annum

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: If you developed a bingo card for the RBA's key phrases in the last 18 months or so, "soft landing" or "narrow path" would be two of your squares. Those phrases were used frequently by former governor Philip Lowe, and they're not going anywhere under Bullock — so it's unsurprising that Senator Bragg asked how we're tracking. Yesterday Treasury Secretary Steven Kennedy (who is also an RBA board member) told Senate estimates that overall, advanced economies had been more resilient to high inflation and restrictive monetary policy (that is, higher interest rates) and the expected path for the "soft landing" to have widened in many, but not all countries. Bragg: "In the Australian context, is our pathway to a soft landing widening or narrowing, or neutral?" Bullock: "I'd say that ... it's probably the same width as it was. And when we say widening, I wouldn't say wide."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Are we going to stick the 'soft landing', or is the pathway widening?

children.content: If you developed a bingo card for the RBA's key phrases in the last 18 months or so, "soft landing" or "narrow path" would be two of your squares.
Those phrases were used frequently by former governor Philip Lowe, and they're not going anywhere under Bullock — so it's unsurprising that Senator Bragg asked how we're tracking.

Yesterday Treasury Secretary Steven Kennedy (who is also an RBA board member) told Senate estimates that overall, advanced economies had been more resilient to high inflation and restrictive monetary policy (that is, higher interest rates) and the expected path for the "soft landing" to have widened in many, but not all countries.
Bragg: "In the Australian context, is our pathway to a soft landing widening or narrowing, or neutral?"
Bullock: "I'd say that ...
it's probably the same width as it was
. And when we say widening, I wouldn't say wide."

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Senator Andrew Bragg picks up on an earlier question asked by Senator Hume, which is whether September's quarterly inflation data was a "material change" because it came in at 1.2%, not 0.9%. Senator Bragg asks Bullock if the September figure does indeed present a "material change". "We're still analysing the number, I'm not prepared to say yet whether or not it's to change to our forecast, because there is going to be a change to our forecasts ," she replies. "We have to look at whether or not it's material enough to change our views on monetary policy ."
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Bullock 'not prepared' to say if inflation will change forecasts enough to affect rates yet

children.content: Senator Andrew Bragg picks up on an earlier question asked by Senator Hume, which is whether September's quarterly inflation data was a "material change" because it came in at 1.2%, not 0.9%.
Senator Bragg asks Bullock if the September figure does indeed present a "material change".
"We're still analysing the number, I'm not prepared to say yet whether or not it's to change to our forecast,
because there is going to be a change to our forecasts
," she replies.
"We have to look at
whether or not it's material enough to change our views on monetary policy

liveBlogPostPrepared.plaintext: Senator Nick McKim is asking questions now and has asked about company profits in high-inflation environments. He asks if it's Bullock's view that corporate profits are not driving inflation. She replies that there is no evidence to suggest that profiteering or profit gouging is taking place. "The evidence is that margins are being maintained and demand is such that it's allowing them to maintain their margins," she says. "Now, you might be able to find particular firms or particular industries where it's such that they are able to increase their margins more than pass on the costs. "But, in aggregate, the evidence is that that's not happening, that basically margins demand is of such an order that they're capable of passing on their costs, but they're not doing more than that." Bullock says there has been no particular evidence or analysis of corporations passing on more than the increase in their costs, but Christopher Kent interjects and says "other than the mining sector", which Bullock agrees with, noting their profit margins have increased because of the global resource prices also trending higher. Bullock adds that the RBA has done some internal analysis, and the conclusion was that profit margins have not widened.
liveBlogPostPrepared.title: Profit margins have not widened despite higher inflation, in RBA's view

children.content: Senator Nick McKim is asking questions now and has asked about company profits in high-inflation environments.
He asks if it's Bullock's view that corporate profits are not driving inflation.
She replies that there is no evidence to suggest that profiteering or profit gouging is taking place.
"The evidence is that margins are being maintained and demand is such that it's allowing them to maintain their margins," she says.
"Now, you might be able to find particular firms or particular industries where it's such that they are able to increase their margins more than pass on the costs.
"But, in aggregate, the evidence is that that's not happening, that basically margins demand is of such an order that they're capable of passing on their costs, but they're not doing more than that."

Bullock says there has been no particular evidence or analysis of corporations passing on more than the increase in their costs, but Christopher Kent interjects and says "other than the mining sector", which Bullock agrees with, noting their profit margins have increased because of the global resource prices also trending higher.
Bullock adds that the RBA has done some internal analysis, and the conclusion was that profit margins have not widened.
